The Prague Stock Exchange fell to minus at the end of trading
After the morning’s sharp decline, the Prague stock exchange corrected losses.
Transactions with <0xC4><0x8C>EZ shares reached almost half of the normal daily trade.
The Prague Stock Exchange has been on its way since the beginning of Tuesday's trading to its Monday downturn, when it fell by almost six percent.
This time, the decline in shares on Wall Street is behind the decline.
This is also how the market reacts to the outcome of the US House of Representatives vote, which refused to support the stabilisation plan for the financial sector there.
Falling Stocks in Asia
The dramatic fall on Tuesday saw stock markets in Asia, although the indexes eventually wiped out some of the losses over the course of the day.
The Hang Seng Index of the Hong Kong Stock Exchange declined nearly four percent during trading, but later wiped out some of the losses and reduced the decline to about 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises Index, which tracks the movement of Chinese stocks on the Hong Kong stock exchange, fell by 3.8 percent, while markets in Shanghai were closed.
Stocks on the Sydney stock exchange lost more than five percent, but eventually lost 4.3 percent.
Taiwan's stock market fell by 3.6 percent on the index.
"The timing of the bailout in the US is uncertain and will affect financial markets around the world," Hong Kong Monetary Authority chief Joseph Yam said in a statement.
Hong Kong, although part of China, determines its monetary policy independently, i.e. independently of the Chinese central bank.
Hong Kong has interest rates at the same level as the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, U.S. lawmakers should quickly return to the negotiations and approve a proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, it is likely that other countries will feel the effects.
The Bloody Bath of American Stocks
The U.S. House of Representatives on Monday rejected a plan to support the financial system, which was supposed to spend up to $700 billion (almost 12 trillion CZK).
Lawmakers ignored President George Bush’s call to support the plan.
According to Bush, the plan would address the root causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
U.S. stocks experienced a bloody spa on Monday, and major stock indexes recorded the biggest drop in more than 20 years.
The Dow Jones index fell nearly seven percent, and it last fell to a similar extent in 1987.
The index fell before the vote, but as soon as it turned out that the proposal did not pass in the House, the index found itself in free fall.
Congress: U.S. government could pump $700 billion into banks
The top representatives of the US Congress and the government of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of agreement on financial assistance for the US financial system.
It will be voted on early next week.
U.S. lawmakers have made a breakthrough in talks to approve a rescue plan in the form of financial aid for the U.S. financial system in the amount of $700 billion (approximately 12 trillion crowns).
However, it is not yet won.
Congressmen must complete some details of the agreement before they can publish the final version of the law and vote on it.
The financial system support plan will be discussed on the floor of the House of Representatives on Monday.
Barney Frank, chairman of the House Banking and Financial Services Committee, told Reuters on Sunday.
According to sources, the Senate could vote on the plan first on Wednesday.
According to economists, the announcement that the rescue plan will be approved should be the first significant psychological factor for the recovery of financial markets.
After that, however, there will be a "cut-off" thanks to the complexity of the mechanisms by which to help markets to achieve even in practice.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
"We have made great progress.
We have resolved our differences on what the shape of the market stabilisation package should look like," Democrat Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
He said the final vote could be held on Sunday.
On Sunday night, lawmakers met with U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson to give a definitive shape to the government fund.
It should buy out unsold mortgage assets from financial companies, which pull financial firms into heavy losses and threaten the stability of the entire system.
"We are on the verge of a definitive agreement on a plan that will work and must also be effective in the market.
We still need to continue with the recovery plan, but I think we’re there,” Paulson said.
Signal for Asian Trade
The global financial crisis is having a significant impact on stock markets, which are falling sharply.
According to Democratic Senator Harry Reid of Nevada, lawmakers are trying to reach a final deal in Congress on Sunday.
They want to reassure investors about trading in Asian financial markets, which are the first in a time zone where a Congressional decision could affect Monday’s trading.
However, it is not yet clear when the two chambers of the US Congress will vote on the law, nor whether they can tie the last-minute negotiations to a problem.
Legislators hope it will be approved in the next few days.
However, the law will see a number of changes.
The total amount intended to assist the system shall be divided into two parts.
The initial $350 billion is expected to be available as soon as possible, as President George Bush has demanded.
However, Congress may block the release of the remaining amount if it feels that the program is not fulfilling its function, in the wake of another $100 billion and later a final $350 billion.
Bush appreciates progress in negotiations
The president may veto this decision, but Congress may override his veto.
Despite these changes, however, the basic idea of the program, which was to obtain finance for the purchase of bad mortgage securities, the value of which has fallen because hundreds of thousands of Americans are unable to repay their mortgages, remained.
"We've worked out everything.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday and the Senate on Monday," Republican Senator Judd Gregg said.
President Bush is also pleased with the progress of the negotiations.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, said Bush was pleased with Saturday’s progress and appreciated “the two-party effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economies.”
Restrictions on gold parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, the chief negotiator, said lawmakers had agreed to take responsibility for the money program, protecting taxpayers from losses, closing reliefs, and timing the financing of the plan.
The new law also aims to limit so-called golden parachutes for directors of companies participating in the program and establishes a committee to oversee the fund.
It should be run by the Ministry of Finance.
“We’ve worked very hard on this, and we’ve made great progress toward a deal that will work and be useful for the market and for all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also includes help for homeowners who have problems with repayment.
The government should negotiate new payments on the mortgages it buys in order to reduce the monthly cost of payments to borrowers and allow them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
According to the chief economist of Patria Finance, David Mark, the proposed plan is a good idea, but it will be very difficult to implement.
“And that’s because we don’t know what mechanism and at what price the troubled assets will be bought out.
This will be decisive for how the financial sector and the government share their losses," Marek told iHNed.cz this week.
Whether the plan will be approved now, or early next week, isn’t all that important, according to Mark.
"It is much more important that this week's congressmen agree that they support this plan and that it is consecrated as soon as possible.
The psychological significance of the agreement that will be approved is the most important at the moment," Marek said.
Battle for Knife Blades: MP3 players against mobiles.
We will advise how to choose
While almost every mobile phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make a phone call.
It seems that it is better to just buy a phone.
Yet there are plenty of reasons why a person should get a separate player.
The choice depends entirely on the method of use and the claims of the future owner.
It’s probably hard to get a top expensive turntable at home to listen to Maxim Turbulenc’s latest album.
However, such music products on LPs do not originate and from a qualitative point of view there is no objective reason for this.
However, if vinyl with art rock, jazz or blues is pressed on your shelves, you probably dream of such a turntable at least.
It is the same with music on the go, that is, music compressed, simplified - music in MP3.
There are also price and quality categories.
For someone, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns per player, as well as Pink Floyd fans will probably find it difficult to test the headphones for twenty crowns from the market.
Two extremes, between which there is enough room for everyone.
The choice is wide.
It also determines the battery life.
Some top-of-the-line music players can do much more than just play music, but what most mobile phones don’t do by chance.
No current device is as versatile as a phone.
In addition to the primary functions, telephony and essay mixing, he can play music and video, record both, he has a better camera, a worse camera and maybe he can even navigate.
And when we take into account smartphones and communicators, you will also have a small computer in your pocket.
It’s a small miracle, because no refrigerator can grill and no TV takes pictures of anything.
The universality of the mobile phone also brings disadvantages.
The more features you use on your phone, the sooner the indicator on the display will send you to the charger.
And playing music is one of the greatest sources of energy.
A small cell phone can play music for more than ten to twelve hours, usually much less.
In this direction, music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
For cheap phones, therefore, count on the fact that they will not play for more than a few hours.
If you still call here and there, get another charger to work for sure - this also applies to more expensive devices.
With MP3 players, you won’t have this problem, even the worst will last at least 9 hours of continuous operation on a single charge.
Another problem occurs when recording music on your mobile phone.
Unfortunately, only a limited number of devices have a universal USB connector, and not all of them can be directly connected to a computer without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly on the memory card, but only a few card readers can cope with the miniature memory cards that are used in mobiles without reduction.
You do not need any special software for players except for the exceptions (iPod).
Just fill the device with music via USB from your computer.
Most mobile phones and players will already create their own music library sorted by the name of the performer, the name of the album, the genre or, for example, the rating of the user.
Some devices display only the tree structure of directories similar to Explorer in Windows, and some are able to both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with the operating system).
Players are easier to use, mobiles are more capable
When choosing a specific device, pay particular attention to the battery life, memory capacity, quality and type of sound output and, of course, the comfort of control.
If your music is mainly behind the scenes and you listen to it every day for a short time, you just need any phone that plays MP3.
This is something that almost any mobile phone can do.
You don’t even have to keep track of what music formats your phone or player can play.
MP3 will handle everything and the vast majority of the music that gets to you will be in this format.
It is one of the most widespread, and in addition to it, the vast majority of devices can handle music in WMA format.
There is less AAC (the format used by Apple and its iPods).
Better mobiles also make it possible, for example, to buy music online.
Simply visit the respective website of the operator (or other provider) via the mobile internet and buy a song or album.
This service could already in itself be a valid argument for the purchase of a music phone.
Unfortunately, the offer of operators is lousy and is mostly limited to fast-paced radio hits.
The prices are also not the lowest.
However, it is generally assumed that this way of selling music (whether via GSM, internet or wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people carry their cell phones with them all the time.
Whenever you get the urge to listen to something, you tap your phone in your pocket while the MP3 player is lying forgotten at home.
However, it still depends on whether you always carry headphones or at least wired handsfree with you.
If not, you can use an integrated speaker that has almost every mobile, but only a minimum of MP3 players.
Perhaps the biggest advantage of music phones will be for many price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand.
For three and four thousand crowns you will already get a very decent walkman.
Most of the time, however, you will be limited by the lack of output to normal headphones.
The best and most technically equipped phones, even with a 3.5 mm hole for ordinary headphones, cost up to fifteen thousand.
The advantage of the players is, among other things, easy operation.
The simplest - not necessarily the cheapest (see our selection) - players can really control everyone.
The minimum of functions, the similarity of the control with a previously common tape recorder or, for example, a turntable is obvious.
There is no risk of collision in the form of a accidentally switched on mobile internet and subsequently a huge account for data transmission.
What device to use
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for exchangeable memory cards (type M2, microSD, etc.).
Even with the purchase of the relevant card, you will get up to two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
For basic models, only cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB are supported.
Only the most expensive ones can cope with 8 GB of memory.
If you already have a mobile and want to buy a cheap MP3 player, reach for Cowon, Creativ, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
According to the capacity (max. 2 GB) you do not have to spend more than 1 100 crowns.
If you are one of the more demanding listeners, you should reach for specialized mobiles - walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have separate control buttons for MP3 and the comfort of operation is thus close to a separate MP3 player.
It is further in the field of Sony Ericsson, whose mobiles from the series walkman have the same user interface as independently sold MP3 players.
The same service and in the same price category up to four thousand crowns, but with a larger memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours), MP3 players will take you away from the above-mentioned brands.
The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer virtually all services as their partners in Western Europe.
Still, we're missing something here - a virtual operator that would make the classics cheaper.
Maybe it won't be long.
About the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe, we have written on Mobil.cz many times.
This was also confirmed by <0xC4><0x8C>TU, which pointed out that the price of SMS is higher in our country than in the rest of the Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming charges, there may be a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are holding so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really wants to go into battle.
Perhaps it sounds paradoxical, after all, we have three mobile networks and penetration high over 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to swear that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
The President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (<0xC4><0x8C>TU) Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xA1>k, who has expressed himself several times in the past that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic, often reminds them of this.
It is probably true that the classical operator with its own network probably no longer has much chance (after all, it would probably be difficult to search for frequencies).
But there is another option - a virtual operator.
It was the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that brought a significant reduction in prices, which then had to be responded to by classic operators.
Even before Tesco Mobile and Virgin Mobile entered the market, voices similar to ours were heard in the UK.
But it turned out that the place for such operators is and can be really successful.
We don’t have to go too far for examples.
In February of this year we informed you about the launch of the Mobilking virtual operator in Poland.
In just half a year, this operator managed to gain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator there.
Behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which in the Czech Republic owns, among other things, U:fona.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more specific target group.
In order for them to function effectively, they need far fewer customers than a conventional operator.
They do not carry with them a relatively high cost for the construction, operation and maintenance of a mobile network.
In the world, virtual operators usually profile as low-cost - they offer cheap calls and SMS, but this is often balanced by a narrower range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
But as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can be quite a good move and a bet on the unscored target group.
This is because the operator is specifically focused on men.
“Administrative guys choose Mobilking – an operator they like and can trust,” says David Seibertz, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which operates this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could be caught in our country.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmented approach, on which the majority of virtual operators are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the supply of services."
In the Czech Republic without a chance, mobile operators say
But it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual mobile operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but the negotiations in the Czech Republic do not look very promising.
Rather, Mobilking will be launched in other countries of our region," Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>kov<0xC3><0xA1>, press spokesperson of the Penta financial group, told Mobil.cz in a telephone interview.
Indirectly, it confirmed that existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not inclined to this idea.
On the contrary, it tries to do everything so that no potential competitor arises.
The GTS Novera Group has not been interested in launching a virtual mobile operator for a long time, which would like to take the next step to become a real competitor of Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
“We are very interested in being able to offer our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner, the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already managed to make progress with some of them in the negotiations," said Pavel Kaidl, a press spokesman for the group.
Maybe they are looking for better times.
From unofficial information, it seems that the first virtual operator we should probably wait until the end of the year.
But for now, its creation is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment, we do not believe that there is room on the Czech market for the creation of a full-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market is very specific compared to other markets.
So far, we have not been approached by any entity with a comprehensive and serious project in this area," Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> from the Press Department of Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2 told Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokesman Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> adds in rare agreement with O2's statement: "So far, we have not recorded any viable and mutually beneficial business project on which it would be possible to build further."
He added: “It’s hard to see a virtual operator in the T-Mobile network until the end of the year.
At this point, we would have to have a specific agreement on the table to be able to think in this short term."
Vodafone prefers to pay attention to meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> says: "By interacting with potential virtual operators, we are open, especially in the area of cost-sharing and infrastructure.
This is what we consider to be the most profitable from the point of view of our customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for fast mobile internet.”
Responsible authorities - with one-handed operators
The procedure of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to a decrease in prices and thus to a decrease in their profits.
So why make it easier for such a competitor?
The fact that when the operators are involved, they can pull one rope, is also evidenced by the pulleys around the creation of U:fon.
Probably the greatest pressure towards CTU was at the time of the creation of the U:phone from T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the <0xC4><0x8C>TU website.
But now U:fon is suitable as an argument for why the virtual operator should not be allowed.
Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> said: "The competitive environment of the mobile market has recently been further strengthened by the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of another player would place high demands on him and, above all, on his services."
Due to this approach of mobile operators, however, the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory authorities is directly striking.
This is not just a CTU position, which unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike the UK and other advanced countries - does not have the power to interfere in economic competition.
These belong exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (OECD).
But he took his typical position on the whole issue.
“The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after the conclusion of a contract between the mobile operator and the virtual operator on the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, as the offer of potential interested parties was probably not interesting enough for classical operators," Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa from the Department of External Relations of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS said in response to our question.
It is not surprising that the representatives of the operators have made such a statement.
From an authority that is supposed to represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, make sure that no one abuses their position on the market, it is more than respectable.
In particular, when Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa adds: “In a foreign country where virtual operators are common, we can observe that their entry into the market has contributed to a reduction in prices for mobile phone services.”
However, the pressure on the correct functioning of the market environment and the fall in prices is not in the interests of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
In fact, it is shocking on the whole case that there is only a touching consonance of three mobile operators, which results from their reactions.
The question of whether it is really just a coincidence, is offered entirely by itself.
Just as the exact same price of petrol at the filling stations is certainly just a coincidence and a fierce competitive battle.
"The Authority has not found any evidence of anti-competitive conduct in this case and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position and therefore has no corresponding increased responsibility for their conduct on the market.
The necessary tools for opening up the mobile market for virtual operators are probably also available to the telecommunications regulator," Chalupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many points of contention.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by <0xC4><0x8C>TU, according to which telecommunications are the only market from the point of view of competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech operators has a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - the creation of a virtual operator always requires the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile operator - quite logically - has a monopoly on its network.
So it must necessarily be dominant in a certain segment.
However, even if we do not accept this argument, it should be at least a warning for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS that the three mobile operators are proceeding in a similar way.
However, complaints from a number of interested parties (including those from GTS Novera) show that they face very similar obstacles when dealing with all operators.
The exercise of responsibility at <0xC4><0x8C>TU is then a fairly common trick in telecommunications, which <0xC3><0x9A>OHS gives away from the whole matter.
We have met with him in a number of similar cases.
Unfortunately, until the recently adopted amendments to the Telecommunications Act, the extension of the powers of the CTU to the field of competition in telecommunications failed to prevail, although a number of experts have since promised to improve the situation.
The <0xC3><0x9A>OHS representatives must know this more than well, but their interests are probably elsewhere.
It goes when no one's looking
At the same time, the functioning of some pseudo-virtual operators remains unnoticed, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that issue their own price lists of mobile phone services, but they are only partially public.
They are usually multi-level marketing companies.
Our own mobile phone services include Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many more.
The prices of these companies usually only reach the chosen ones.
The magic lies in the fact that the company acts as a classic corporate customer in relation to the operator, who orders a large number of SIM cards.
As a significant customer, he will then receive special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the terms and conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit a similar resale.
"If there are cases that you are talking about, it could be a violation of the contractual terms that we would deal with and could result in the termination of cooperation with the company in question," Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> answered our question on this issue.
However, it is highly unlikely that such activities would not be carried out by mobile operators to responsible people.
In particular, in the case of the three mentioned companies, there may be thousands of customers.
None of the operators are prevented from doing so.
In fact, these companies have negligible profits from their activities and, unlike real virtual operators, they do not threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> points out possible problems: "The law allows for similar speculation, but only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
In addition, they must accept that the SIM card in their phone is not held in their name, so they cannot have it fully available as regular customers of mobile operators."
That’s what should be at least weird.
In addition, another question is opened for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If mobile operators are blindfolded by a similar procedure, why are they blocking the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has relatively strong powers to disclose such activities, and if it does not want to, it may not be satisfied with the operators’ explanation that they have no idea of such a thing and their trading conditions prohibit it.
When we are not the most expensive
As has already happened several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought a noticeable drop in prices for services.
In almost all countries where virtual operators were created, classical operators tried to more or less defend their creation.
The arguments used by Jimi were virtually identical - too small or possibly too saturated a market, problems with the quality of service, etc.
In developed countries, however, it is precisely at this time that regulatory authorities have intervened, which have defended not the interests of mobile operators, but their customers.
Whether by formal measures or informal pressure, they achieved that the first virtual operator was created and others packed on it.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory authorities are throwing the whole case away like a hot potato.
From our experience, we cannot get rid of the impression that ambiguities in competences are more than suitable for them in these cases.
But let's not throw flint in the grain.
If the behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator is really soon to appear in our company, the Czech mobile market may be shifting again.
If one of the operators has admitted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it will be difficult for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS to remain in a position to refuse (discrimination) other interested parties.
And maybe we'll stop calling the rails than in the rest of Europe.
