Even rats have feelings.
When a rat or a cockroach flees from danger, does that mean they also feel fear?
Neurologist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that even many animals have feelings.
But how would it be possible to verify whether they feel the same when they behave like us?
In the online magazine "Edge" for several years, contributions of well-known scientists are published.
SPIEGEL ONLINE in its series presents selected answers to the question "What do you consider to be true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have feelings and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else being able to prove it until now, when we cannot prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case we can at least hope, because all human brains have the same basic configuration.
However, as soon as we begin to engage in a different kind and open up questions of perception or general consciousness, we enter the impassable terrain because the hardware does not match.
When a rat gets into danger, it will do the same thing as many other animals: pretend to be dead, flee or attack.
Humans behave in a similar way, from which some scientists suggest a comparable subjective experience.
But I don't believe it.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to the experience of animals.
This is because the circuits associated with human consciousness almost always include the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its share of short-term memory and executive or control functions).
This vast area is much more developed in humans than in other primates, and seems to be completely lacking in other creatures.
At least in those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, among them the knowledge of who we are, and the ability to plan and decide, there is reason to believe that man is different from even other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity could be hidden by the language essence of man: because so much of his perception is associated with language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, we could exclude animals.
But even if consciousness did not depend on language, language would certainly influence it, so that animal consciousness, however constructed, would probably differ from most states of our consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to find out what consciousness looks like in other animals.
When, as something internal and subjective, it can neither be measured nor analyzed on the basis of our own experience, due to special hardware, its exploration puts us in front of great problems.
Most of my findings relate to the content of conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more scientifically accessible.
It would be possible to study processes in the consciousness of animals regardless of their content, and this is exactly what happens in studies of short-term memory in primates, especially on the example of visualization.
But this approach, which Christof Koch and Francis Crick focused on, focuses more on the neural correlates of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: both may be identical, but they may not be.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the non-frontal cortex for the realization of visualization.
What does that mean for feelings?
I derive them from the fact that an emotional system, such as a fear system, is activated in the brain by conscious self-activity.
What we call “fear,” then, is the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of a defense system localized in the brain (or its consequences, such as bodily reactions) takes advantage of the operating memory.
Seen from this angle, the sensations are closely associated with those areas of the cortex that are characterized by primates, and especially humans.
In connection with language nature, there is a subtle degradation of perception, because with the help of words and grammar, we can distinguish and categorize states in order to attribute them to each other and to others.
On the other hand, Antonio Damasio, for example, believes that feelings arise from more primitive activities in the areas of the cortex and brain stem devoted to bodily sensations, much like Jaak Pankseep, who focuses more on the brain stem.
Since this network has not changed much in the course of human evolution, it could easily participate in the feelings perceived by several animal genera.
In theory, I can't argue with that, but I think it's unprovable.
Pankseep argues that what we think of as fear in rats and humans is likely to be felt by both organisms in the same way: But how is it possible to verify, Pankseep goes on to say, whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave similarly?
The cockroach flees from danger - does he also feel fear?
From my point of view, the mere similarity of behavior cannot prove the consistency of experience.
It is true that the neural comparison moves us further: rats and humans have similar brain strains, in contrast to cockroaches and brains.
But is the brain stem responsible for feelings?
And even if it were possible to prove it in humans: how would we want to prove it in rats?
I think rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?), have feelings.
But I really don't know how to prove it.
And because their feelings are probably fundamentally different from ours (because human consciousness is based on special circuits and language), I’d rather explore emotional behavior than emotional perception of rats.
In any case, in this case, we can expect to see progress at the neural level if we measure the same thing in rats and humans.
Like rats, I don’t examine language and consciousness, I don’t even examine feelings, because I don’t know if they exist.
It is possible to consider it short-sighted, but I prefer to move forward rather than repeatedly throwing myself against the wall.
I'm a practical emotionalist.
