Some people think that the street got its name in 1802, when Philip Minthorna's large farm was divided among several of his children and no one claimed that narrow strip of land.
The back door to the Extra Place was led by CBGB, a punk rock monument that closed in 2006, and the street is perhaps best known as the background to the photo on the Ramones album "Rocket to Russia".
"The place was amazing," says Danny Fields, manager of the Ramones, who took the photo in November 1976.
"It was full of garbage, torn clothes and pieces of barrels, posters, leaves and ropes."
Some locals, including bloggers who write about grooming the East Village neighborhood, oppose the idea of selling Extra Place and argue that that piece of public property, though modest, should remain public.
Others consider Extra Place to be a rarity - an almost unchanged part of the city that should be left as it is.
Jeremiah Moss, who writes a blog called Jeremiah's Disappearing New York (subtitled "The Book of Lamentations: A bitterly nostalgic view of the city in the process of extinction"), penned part of the Extra Place story from Talk About the City, which appeared in The New Yorker newspaper in 1952.
The author of the article, Brendan Gill, wrote: "Extra Place is a narrow blind alley, dark even in the daytime and bordered by rusty iron warehouse doors and clogged windows, where a week's worth of old newspapers are chased in the straws."
With a few exceptions, the street of one recent evening looked exactly the same.
The rat passed through the blind end of the street near the door that once led to the CBGB, where today stands a store of expensive clothing.
There was graffiti on the walls and next to the fresh dose of discarded newspapers lay an empty bottle of beer.
A couple of passers-by said they rarely thought of Extra Place, but suggested that it might be worth some effort.
Fields, on the other hand, said he thinks some people underestimate the street’s appeal in its current state.
"The best years of my life," he said, "were in places of darkness, dampness, and disgust."
The Bilingualism Debate: Immersion in English
In this issue of Focused on Education, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi will discuss the attitudes of candidates to bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, a Californian academic and director of education at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is co-author of “Borse Than You Think: Why Middle Class Needs Schools.”
Effectively addressing Hispanic voters is a sham business.
Barack Obama’s education agenda is proof of that.
Obama’s campaign notes that “African-American and Hispanic students are significantly less likely to study than white students,” which is true.
In order to combat such performance differences, Obama’s education agenda specifically advocates, among other things, “transitional bilingual education” for those who are just learning English.
The question, however, remains whether Barack Obama’s commitment to bilingual education, which emphasizes the use of languages other than English in the classroom, is stronger than his interest in reducing performance differences.
Take, for example, Sixth Street Prep, a charter elementary school in East Los Angeles County.
The students of this school are, in the vast majority of cases, Hispanics from low-income families.
More than a third of students, many of whom have only recently arrived, are still learning English.
Nevertheless, in the state tests of mathematics in 2008, it reached the highest level of an incredible hundred percent of fourth-grade students.
Almost equally amazing ninety-three percent of fourth-grade students reached the highest level in state tests of English language and literature.
This incredible success has been achieved by a different method than Obama prefers.
Sixth Street emphasizes control and practice, constant assessment of abilities, and unexplainable approach.
Further, and Obama should note, according to Linda Mikels, director of Sixth Street, the school’s pedagogical approach for those who are just learning English is “complete immersion.”
Immersion in English emphasizes the almost exclusive use of English in teaching.
Ms. Mikels, who is opposed to bilingual education, told me, “We had a tremendous success with one brand-new student from Mexico – after twelve months, you would enter the class and not know who it is.”
"It works," she said, "it works for us."
Would Obama take a school like Sixth Street Prep as an example of what other schools with large shares of Hispanic and English-students should look like?
The results that the school achieves should make it obvious from the answer to this question, but the educational agenda of its own party (the National Education Association is a long-standing supporter of bilingual education) and its own consistent support of bilingual education make it unclear.
While Obama agrees that immigrants should learn English, he has recently trivialized the matter by saying that people should stop worrying about “English-only” laws.
Instead, "you should make sure your children speak Spanish," he said.
If Obama really wants to erase performance differences, he should think more carefully about the educational patterns that work, rather than making fun of them and trivializing them.
Oil is falling sharply due to renewed economic concerns
Oil prices fell sharply on Monday amid concerns that not even a U.S. bailout plan would have to revive the economy.
In the morning trading on the New York Commodity Exchange, the prices of oil futures fell by 7 percent to $99.80 per barrel.
Since last Monday, prices have fallen by more than twenty dollars per barrel.
In the past two weeks, commodity markets have been rocked by financial unrest on Wall Street and a pair of powerful hurricanes in the Gulf of Mexico.
After reaching a maximum of $145.29 per barrel in July, prices fell to nearly $90 per barrel earlier this month, sparking a surge in financial market uncertainty.
Investors were once again gripped by anxiety on Monday, even after the Congressional presidency announced it had reached an agreement over the weekend on the biggest bailout plan in history.
This report was overshadowed by fresh concerns that the financial crisis is far from over.
In the latest episode of the ongoing breakup, the government announced that Citigroup will buy Wachovia Corporation’s banking division.
In the meantime, the Belgian, Dutch and Luxembourg governments have partially liquidated the European financial conglomerate Fortis.
Analysts at Barclays Capital said the frantic weekend talks that led to the plan to save the economy “showed to be unable to revive the market mood.”
As the economic situation worsens, demand for commodities, including oil, is expected to decline.
“The outlook for global equities, interest rates and exchange rates has been severely eroded,” Deutsche Bank analysts wrote in a report to investors.
"We believe that commodities will not be able to escape the disease.
From a commodity perspective, our biggest concern is the extent to which the U.S. virus will spread around the world and especially to China.”
Analysts at the bank lowered their expectations for next year as oil consumption fell due to slower economic growth, and lowered their 2009 gasoline price forecasts by about 20 percent.
