The Pride and Obstacles of Black Lives in a Separate City
Hidden among the sprawling amusement parks of Greater Orlando, a few miles from everything shiny, noisy and huge, lies a quiet city where the pride and sophistication of African-American life comes to life.
Eatonville, the first completely black city to be incorporated into the state and where Zora Neale Hurston spent her childhood, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: “the city of five lakes, three croquet courts, three hundred brown skins, three hundred good schools, and three hundred good floats.”
It is now a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee attended the annual Eatonville Festival Zora! to pay tribute to Hurston, the most famous female writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
The city she described remains a sideline, even though it has made it a tourist stop by including it in the Florida tourist guide created by the Federal Writers Project during the economic crisis.
It’s still as independent, dignified, and private as it was in the 1930s when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted and didn’t share their true feelings with a white man who “knows so little about us that he doesn’t even know what he’s missing.”
Even today, in a year when the black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, is calling for an open debate about races, many of the people here remain wary of the views of foreigners.
“We pay close attention to how our story is told,” says 59-year-old Hortense Jones, who has lived here since birth and is a member of the city’s oldest parish.
"It must be right."
Eatonville has long been characterized as a paradox of triumph and effort.
It is both a historical model of the Black rise and a community of nearly 2,400 people, where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is a center of literature, but also a shady example of southern rural black culture – sometimes despised, sometimes praised – that originated from American slavery.
It is not surprising that the people here are both proud and protective.
And concerns about Eatonville's idea really started with Zora, which is the only way the Hurstons are called here.
She introduced her hometown to the world through heart-wrenching books such as Mules and Men (1935) and Their Eyes Were Watching God (1937).
The five paragraphs of the Florida tour guide turned the city into road no. 17, which leads through the often overlooked center of Florida, into a stage of black history and human drama.
With the start of a big drum in life and literature, Hurston introduced readers to the shop of Eatonville's first mayor, Joe Clark, and then turned to more personal places.
"To the left of the road," she wrote, "is a white, brownly decorated modern national school with well-maintained courtyards and playgrounds that Howard Miller always cares about, even though he can't read or write much."
She also mentioned Dash's widow's new husband, writing that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds and anything that fits the hour hotel."
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston connected Eatonville with self-government, but also with illiteracy, remarriage and sex.
This was obviously not typical of Fodor's publishing house.
In fact, it wasn’t a portrait that everyone would appreciate.
"Zora said it the way it was," says 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of Johnson's girls who made Hurston immortal by citing men who sang downright songs about their beauty.
"Some people didn't like it," she added.
Hurston is still remembered here as a chip-cutter who often returned after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Seventy-seven-year-old Augustus Franklin remembers that most of the time, when she came to town, she arrived unannounced in a huge Chevrolet, smoked, and wore pants in a city that is still proud of its dignified dress.
Most of the population was fascinated, Franklin said, but many were scolded.
"The people of Zora have always loved to see," Franklin said.
But, he added, he swings on a chair on the back terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, "never stayed too long."
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were cut from the press.
It seemed that Eatonville had forgotten about her along with the rest of the world.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she had previously lived.
There were no major funerals or public readings in Eatonville.
"I don't think they understood either her significance to the world or her legacy at all," said Valerie Boyd, author of Hurston's 2003 biography Wrapped in Rainbows.
The change came in the 80s of the 20th century.
Orange County County officials wanted to extend the city by a five-lane highway instead of Kennedy Boulevard, a local two-lane highway.
Orland's ascent has already pushed Interstate 4 through the western edge of the city.
The proposal came at a time when Eatonville was still receiving from a difficult historical period.
Forced integration, along with other things, ended the relatively idyllic isolation of this community.
In the 1950s, the struggle to stir up racial hatred brought it to the forefront of the community.
"At that time, a bunch of white guys, they came and threw oranges and things at people who were sitting on the sidelines," Franklin said.
"We actually had one lady here who killed it.
They were walking melon out of the car."
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston challenged the Supreme Court’s demand for forced integration and declared his decision in Brown’s case against the Board of Education to be “offensive rather than laudatory to my race.”
Residents now claim that desegregation of schools, while positive in some areas, has reduced cohesion in Eatonville and undermined the courage of the local youth.
"Black kids were used to hugging - I remember that - you hugged your teacher in the morning, you hugged your teacher in the evening," said N. Y. Nathriova, daughter of Elly Dinkins and executive director of the nonprofit group Preserve the Eatonville Community.
It lasted until the teachers and students came from the same place, she added.
"You're not embracing your white teacher because your white teacher -- I mean, there's a cultural barrier," Ms. Nathiri said.
Civil rights, however, helped to create space for many more Zora Neale Hurston - black writers, actors and artists who, like her, rose above prejudices with light-hearted self-confidence and quotes such as "How can anyone deny the pleasure of my presence!
I don't understand."
In 1975, Alice Walker arrived at Hurston's unmarked grave and began fighting to revive her reputation.
Five years later, a highly acclaimed biography of Robert E. Hemenway by Robert E. Hurston came to the shelves of bookstores, which again included her in the American canon.
The highway project arrived just as Eatonville’s most famous daughter found the lights of the ramp again.
The former neighbors of Hurston now considered her a saviour.
To show what could happen to their highway, the community began planning the 1988 Hurston Festival.
Thousands of fans arrived for the inaugural event two years later, and many return to the celebration each January.
A few years later, the state withdrew from the highway proposal.
"The five currents of the highway have risen, you would say, directly ignited, real civic pride," Nathiri said.
Boyd said it more simply, "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory over the highway project helped change the image of the city.
Out-of-towners like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who began attending the church here in 1993, began to appear in greater numbers, and residents began to reassess the past.
Eatonville joined the National Historical Register in 1998.
The new one-story library (named, of course, after Hurston) was opened in 2006 on the newly paved and beautified Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains a Florida anomaly: just six miles from downtown Orlando can sometimes seem like a dead end in summer rain, as small as when it was founded with only 27 black families in the 1980s.
(Ninety percent of them are black.)
With strangers coming to look for the story and meaning of Eatonville, it is still often treated with caution.
Permission for most interviews is required in advance and certain things – such as murals in the oldest Eatonville church painted by whites and depicting blacks in the fields – are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Jones, a brave, self-confident teacher who likes bright red, still fear that their isolated community will not be properly understood.
And even as the Hurston Festival grew, so did domestic pride.
Especially young people tend to see Eatonville the way Hurston saw her whole race: beautiful, troubled, and so on, but no better, no worse, and as proud, creative, hardworking, foolish, and diverse as any other American race and ethnic group.
The voice of Franklin’s nephew, eighteen-year-old Edwin Harvey, sounds like a sincere love for the village as he plans to return to Eatonville after college to work in a local government or police department he says would benefit from some help.
And even younger ones, such as eleven-year-old twins from Winter Park Alondra and Alexia Kenonova, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people, when they're just passing through here, think, 'Hm, this town is nothing against the others,' " Alondra Kenon said recently Sunday after church.
"But if you really stop and look at history for a moment, it's a very nice city."
