Drivers repeatedly caught with alcohol in their blood will have to install an "alcolock"
The Ministry of the Interior requires that a driver with three administrative penalties for driving under the influence of alcohol must install a system in his car that will prevent him from starting the car intoxicated or if he does not breathe.
The proposal was announced in June of this year and is now included in the annual report of the Supreme State Prosecutor’s Office, according to which it is a pilot project that will last one year.
Its goal is to return the driver behind the wheel, so drivers will also have to take a transport retraining course.
In addition to the National Transportation Safety Authority, the Directorate-General for Transport (DGT) and the Foundation of the Institute of Technology for Automobile Safety (FITSA) will also participate in this experience.
According to statistics, between 30 and 75% of motorists accused of driving drunk more than once will sit behind the wheel again in this state.
Alcolock should avoid this, as it is a system connected to a vehicle that measures the level of alcohol in the exhaust air and prevents the car from starting if the driver does not breathe beforehand or if there is a higher than permissible concentration of alcohol.
His price exceeds 1,000 euros and it would have to be paid by the culprit himself.
A study carried out in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with this device had a 65% reduction in offences during the first year since its introduction.
In Spain, it is estimated that 115 people could be saved each year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to address this behaviour before it results in a criminal offence.
And to help implement it, since the legislation can be carried out in the usual way, the necessary modification of criminal provisions requires a change in the law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any sales version, although some industrial vehicles and public service vehicles have already been tested.
Tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote on the PSOE (Spanish Workers’ Socialist Party) proposal, which recommends installing this system on school buses, as is the case in France.
