Talking from sleep
Some children talk at night.
I don't mean those who wake up and tell us something that happened the day before, but children who talk while they sleep.
When it happens for the first time, it may scare you, but in fact, it’s meaningless.
This is a harmless sleep disorder called somnilloquia.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure none of you were told he was talking in his sleep last night.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (for example, once a lifetime in high fevers), or with more regularity (every day, once a week, once a few months...), the second day the child does not remember anything.
There is not a single reason for her arrival.
It is often associated with other sleep disorders, such as nightmares, night rage, nocturnal enuresis (nighttime help) or flatulence, but this may not be the case.
As mentioned earlier, it can often accompany very high fevers, stressful or aggravated situations.
In any case, this is a little-studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also different.
The child can speak in a calm voice, say individual words, whisper, or just the opposite (screams, crying, long speeches...).
In cases where it manifests with great force, it would be appropriate to observe and consult with a specialist to see if he has any problem that causes him great anxiety and thus manifests itself.
We said that it is a harmless disorder, therefore it is not treated, only if it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with apnea syndrome or with permanent stress).
However, we can do this by keeping in mind a few very simple preventive measures, such as:
Try not to disturb the baby too much before going to sleep.
So look for quiet games and avoid scary or somewhat violent TV shows or serials.
In very nervous children and those who give the job to relax, it is possible to use relaxation techniques that will help them to get some inner peace.
This will allow the child to sleep more peacefully.
When somnolence appears, try to remain calm.
Remember that it is harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember anything of what happened.
Helpful Advice
Don't be him.
It's useless, because he's not conscious and you're interrupting his sleep.
Even when he speaks, he sleeps, and therefore rests.
Remember that if you think several times in a row that you are very worried, it would be advisable to seek advice or find out what causes such anxiety in a child.
If he understands what he is saying (which is not so common), avoid the temptation to interrogate him and extract information from him.
It won't do any good, because when he's asleep, he's not conscious of being able to organize his thoughts.
In addition, you will hear what he says, but you do not know what he thinks, and therefore why he says it, so pay close attention to how you interpret the information and what conclusions you come to.
Never tell a child that you can ask him about his secrets at night.
It's not funny.
That's causing a lot of anxiety.
Don’t worry, it’s not a bad thing, it’s just an episode that only lasts a few minutes.
