Interview - Blood That's Sure Again
Héma-Québec celebrated its tenth anniversary yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was justifiably pleased as Héma-Québec became one of the most reliable and effective blood suppliers in the world.
Above all, he regained the trust of the public, which was seriously shaken after the blood-contaminated scandal of the 1980s and 1990s.
As is generally known, the national blood supply administered by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Department was contaminated during the 1980s by the immune deficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus.
In view of this drama and wave of public unrest, the Canadian government launched a public inquiry in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, aimed at explaining the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and making recommendations that such a disaster should never happen again.
While Judge Krever hesitated to deliver the report, some provinces set in motion a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélinea Committee took on this role.
Following the Gélineau and Krever report, two suppliers were established in Canada: Héma-Québec, which was to manage Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all provinces and both territories.
“When Héma-Québec started its activities in 1998, only 38% of people still had confidence in the Quebec blood system,” says Dr. Décary.
"The situation was disconcerting.
Through our consistent efforts to increase the safety of blood products, and our continued work in this area over the next few years, we have regained public confidence," he says, adding proudly that at the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of the Quebec population trusted Héma-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary does not lose sight of the fact that "trust is something very fragile".
Since its establishment on September 28, 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
"We witnessed many cases of human form mad cow disease in Europe back then, a new variant of the disease called Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease," says the woman, who has led the company since its founding in 1998.
"And we didn't know if this disease could spread blood.
We have therefore relied on one of the basic recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which, in the event that we do not know and when a serious disease is at stake, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by degeneration of the brain inevitably leads to death.
In April 1999, we therefore refused blood from people who had been in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
A few years ago, it was safely proven that this disease is transmitted by blood.
So this episode showed us that it made sense to stick to the precautionary principle.”
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting the HIV virus appeared on the market: tests using nucleic acid (NAT), which allow to detect in donor blood directly the presence of the virus itself, and not the presence of antibodies on which the tests used before were based.
NAT tests have made it possible to shorten the deafening period that occurs between the moment of infection of the patient and the moment when our techniques can detect the first viruses in the blood, explains the specialist.
We were able to shorten this period to less than a week.
We have significantly reduced the risk that some donors could be infected without them knowing about it and without us being able to figure it out.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of getting AIDS through blood transfusions.
One in 12 million people are at risk of getting HIV-contaminated blood.
“In other words, it means that before anyone gets HIV, 12 million blood products will need to be distributed.
Since Héma-Québec distributes 400,000 to 500,000 blood products annually, it will take 24 years for the first case of HIV transmission through the blood product to appear.
I believe that today we can safely get or prescribe the transfusion of blood necessary for healing," says Héma-Québec.
“The challenge for the next decade is to keep our products safe.
We never know what disease-causing element may appear in the system.
Just last year, a chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted into the blood by suffocating insects.
It is necessary to be constantly cautious," continues Dr. Décary, stressing that in addition to safe supply, Héma-Québec must also count on sufficient supply.
“Needs are growing because the population is getting older.
As a result of more aggressive cancer treatment, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has implications for the blood donor network, which on average consists of only 3% of Quebecers eligible to donate."
Every healthy person is at least 18 years old, meeting the eligibility criteria, but can donate blood only once in 56 days, that is, six times a year.
14% of people offering blood are not accepted on average because they are, for example, carriers of AIDS or malaria, and if they have visited a country where marshy colds are managed, they are excluded for a period of one year.
"With these 3%, we can maintain a state that meets the needs of hospitals.
Deficiencies are very rare.
However, the members of the donor network need to be supplemented in proportion to how old they are and can no longer donate blood.
However, it is difficult to convince people to donate blood, especially to keep it and encourage them to become regular donors.
Life is so unchained today that we rarely find an hour to donate blood," Francine Décary said.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissue, such as bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin, which is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Hém-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord, previously thought to be biomedical waste, is overflowing with blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“A few weeks ago, we celebrated the deposit of our 1,000 umbilical cord blood samples to the bank and we expect to collect over 1,000 blood samples per year.
At the beginning of next year, we should start offering them for transplants," says Dr. Décary, who describes the cord blood collection program as very popular.
"Some moms are disappointed that they don't have access to it," because Héma-Québec doesn't have enough funds to offer this comprehensive and expensive program to all hospitals in Quebec.
