Opinions - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Discourse
In a September 17 issue, Le Devoir printed a letter from Patrick J. Garver, executive vice president of Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
With Orwellian logic, he confirms that the world's largest gold producer has launched a prosecution of three authors and a poor small publishing house for insulting honor in order to spark a "transparent public debate" and demands six million from them.
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, they do not judge the truth, especially in the case of prosecution for an insult to honor, but the law.
It is not surprising that Garver completely misses this crucial distinction.
Or is it the best way for Barrick Gold to conduct a public debate, to bring to ruin anyone who would dare to defend the opposite position?
Whatever the case may be, the authors and publisher of the book Noir Canada (Black Canada) will be forced to spend respectable sums to be prepared to defend themselves and fight in a very unbalanced battle with an army of lawyers backed by the almost bottomless pockets of a mining company.
Tactics in these unbalanced struggles, after all, often consist in ruining the defendants in order to enforce a conciliation procedure that will silence the mouth of the opposing party and, moreover, frighten anyone who would dare to devote himself to this matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it had to present its view of the whole thing to the public.
Contrary to what is happening in several countries where Barrick Gold operates, in Canada, the debate in normal circumstances lies in the exchange of ideas, and not in the wounds of a shoe.
Mining companies, therefore, had no choice but to open their books, their documentation, and establish a real debate through newspapers, media, publications and funding of independent scientific teams that could bring light to the whole thing.
Barrick Gold, however, seems to have no confidence in public opinion and sneers at petitions and letters in support of the authors of Noir Canada.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he could demand a "public debate" while at the same time repudiating the views of the same public?
It seems that in the vice president’s world, this word only refers to fat-paid lawyers, and not all Canadians; it’s a pretty narrow concept of this term.
In a democracy, even whistleblowers have the right to speak.
Barrick Gold does not understand - or does not want to understand - that the public, which supports the authors and publishers of Noir Canada, does so primarily because it rejects the brutal ways of mining society.
The public is prepared to hear Barrick and judge the case, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, not within what many perceive as a prosecution, in which the defendant is to have his mouth shut (in the context of his prosecution of the "public debate" Barrick, by the way, has just filed a formal challenge to the Canadian author to have him prosecuted).
By way of the surreal Garver speech, the prosecution of the initiated Barrick Gold is a direct attack on the university’s freedom to investigate and seek the truth that is essential to any democratic society.
In general, it denies the right to quote credible sources and to debate the facts and interpretations that constitute the very basis of intellectual activity.
If, in a country like Canada, it is impossible to study and discuss issues that the rich companies of this world do not like, without being subjected to repeated prosecution, who else will be able to do it?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could have formed it if it followed the scientific standards used by the authors of Noir Canada.
He has the right of reply.
The university environment to which we belong has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s exaggerated claim clearly shows that, despite what it claims, it does not have the slightest inclination to lead a transparent debate.
It’s a loss for the university world, as well as for the public debate in Canada, and it’s time for governments to put in place measures that would limit this type of unauthorized prosecution.
Operation to save Wall Street - Democrats and Republicans understand each other
Yesterday, the Bush administration and the leaders of Congress, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement on the biggest bailout since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
A new version of the plan to use $700 billion to stem the financial crisis that has been brewing on Wall Street for months has yet to be approved by both chambers of Congress.
In particular, it envisages: better control of the elected representatives over its application, new mechanisms to ensure the payment of the public money saved, new measures to capture the number of houses seized due to non-payment, and the right to monitor the amount of wages paid to the executives of the rescued companies.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, Speaker of the House of Representatives Nancy Pelosi and Republican Representative to the table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced this good news just minutes after midnight yesterday, after the two-day negotiating marathon ended.
"We have made great progress and reached an agreement that will be effective in the markets," Bush administration spokesman Henry Paulson said.
“Everything has been done to keep the real economy and ordinary Americans safe from the crisis that is taking place on Wall Street,” he said.
“This is a crucial point: if we don’t do this, the trauma, chaos and disruption of Americans’ daily lives will be huge,” said Republican Judd Gregg.
Over the last few hours, the negotiations have started at maximum turnarounds out of fear of the effect that another failure would have on investor sentiment.
The deadline was set for the markets to open this morning.
Both candidates for the U.S. president were invited to the negotiations later, and both expressed themselves rather for the agreement, but did not forget to express their dissatisfaction with the fact that it was necessary to resort to such a final solution.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has credited himself with supplementing the agreement with some measures, in particular those aimed at enabling homeowners to preserve their homes, and wage measures for state-run labor-saving companies.
"When we ask taxpayers to take special measures due to the irresponsibility of some people, there is nothing to congratulate on.
However, these measures are necessary," he explained on TV waves.
His Republican rival John McCain, who was asked by another station if he would vote for the proposed plan, replied, "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
“The rough features I’ve read [show] that it’s something that we’re all going to have to spend and use to move forward.
To choose inaction is simply unacceptable," he said.
The goal of the $700 billion plan is to buy back dubious receivables and risky and unsold assets of U.S. financial institutions for taxpayers’ money.
The plan comes after 14 months of a crisis triggered by a bubble burst in the real estate market that first led to the collapse of risky mortgage loans (subprimes), then transferred to other, more widespread forms of credit (PCAA) and resulted in the freezing of cash and the breakdown of banks and financial institutions.
The collapse of the first draft of the agreement from last week is on the minds of Republican lawmakers.
From the moment the Democrats have agreed that some of the “toxic” assets of struggling companies will only be guaranteed by the government, but will not buy them, there is a belief that the situation is ablaze.
In an effort to reconcile conflicting views in Congress, measures were added that would allow the government to introduce new fees that would help it get its deposit back if it had to take over losses for five years as a result of the program.
The new plan includes a first deposit of $250 billion, to which an additional $100 billion can be added if the president deems it necessary.
A further <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>350 billion should be approved by Congress in a new vote.
In exchange for his help, Washington will get shares in the salvaged companies, which will pay him dividends in the event of a profit, and which he will be able to resell when it is over.
The federal government will be able to delay the procedures for seizing the properties associated with the loans covered by the plan, as well as set limits on the amount of valuations and compensation paid to executives of affected companies.
The plan's guardians would like to have it voted in the House of Representatives today and in the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all the efforts made, it is not yet certain whether their plan will have a green one.
Yesterday, voices continued to rise against this project, both in the republican and in the democratic camp.
"It's perfectly clear that Washington doesn't hear you," Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, told voters.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
However, making money on taxpayers is not the solution.”
Democratic Rep. Brad Sherman, the moderator of a group of congressmen dubbed the “committee of skeptics,” presents the whole thing differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred distinguished professors of economics, including three Nobel laureates, wrote to us: 'We ask Congress not to be in too much of a hurry and to examine carefully which way to go,'" he said.
At the same time, Europe has once again confirmed that this crisis is a world crisis.
After the extraordinary meeting, three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalisation of the banking group Fortis for <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>11.2 billion (USD 16.3 billion).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was withdrawing from the purchase of its competitor, which has been on the verge of collapse since it lost 2 billion euros ($2.9 billion) due to a crisis of non-performing loans.
Fortis employs 85,000 people, is among the 20 largest European banks and among the 10 largest insurers.
"We will not lose that money," Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
"In return, we gain the right to vote in the bank and influence.
And it is precisely the gardeners and households who can appreciate this in today’s uncertain time.”
On the other side of the La Manche Channel, it seems, the British government has begun to nationalize another bank affected by the financial crisis.
