Paul Newman (1925-2008) - Death socially engaged icon
His beauty with azure eyes has long represented his trump card, according to other weaknesses.
Did this American actor come out with a charming smile from narcissism?
Yes and no.
The shyness, sensitivity and unbridled talent of his own also distanced him from the power category that breeds true stars.
But what a long-distance runner he was!
Paul Newman died on Friday at the age of 83 on his Connecticut ranch from lung cancer and remains one of the last icons of the fat years of American cinema.
Less magnanimous than Brando, to whom he was similar and for a long time his rival on the film screen, Newman was a more careful actor, certainly more fragile, but also an apostle of freedom and the breakdown of dramatic conventions.
Mixed blood often produces beautiful children.
Born in Ohio in 1925, his father was a German Jew and his mother was of Hungarian descent.
From these European roots, one of the famous faces of the American dream was born.
Without excessive ego, which is the last sign of quality.
Because it looked at the whole country in love with self-made mana, a warrior in the war in the Pacific, wounded in a battle that in the early 1950s studied acting at Yale, then visited New York's Actor's Studio and celebrated triumph in theater, television and theater.
The same man who fought for civil rights was also an automobile racer, who placed second at the 1979 24 Hours of Le Mans, and at the same time a sexual symbol, despite having formed a model couple with actress Joanne Woodward since 1958.
It also takes away the shadowy places of this hidden, discreet, socially engaged star, allergic to the whims of his own show-business, which will forever remain a mystery to some extent.
A good man, in the highest sense of the word.
The departure of Paul Newman this weekend has caused a stir for film lovers, while his big roles compete together on a black canvas of memories.
After him, he parades for more than half a century the ever-changing American seventh art.
A charming cowboy emerges from Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid (1969), a young man who rejects his sensuous wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in The Cat on the Burnt Roof, a 1958 Tennessee Williams adaptation.
From the less distant past (1990) we remember his sensitive Mr. Bridge, troubled at an advanced age by marriage that did not meet all expectations.
So many other Paul Newmans have gone down in history.
Boxer Rocky Graziano, a battered, violent, unforgettable delinquent from Somebody Up There Likes Me by Robert Wise, a role intended for James Dean, taken after his death, which Newman made real acquaintance in 1956.
A sympathetic gangster in the absolutely great The Sting (Podraz), Oscar for Best Picture in 1973.
A bitter and vengeful billiards player in Robert Rossen's The Hustler (1961), the same character will appear in Martin Scorsese's The Color of Money, bringing him the only Oscar in 1987 out of seven nominations.
This face of a traveling age, it was him.
And him again.
In his professional career, different eras compete with each other.
He is best known for the iconic George Roy Hill Slap Shot (1977) from the role of Reggie Dunlop, an unconventional hockey coach.
Fans met him again in 1994 in The Hudsucker Proxy of the Coen brothers.
He ended his career as the Irish mob boss in Sam Mendes' Road to Perdition in 2003.
Unlike a few movie legends who pretty soon left the craft, Newman remained in the industry for a long time, though he did condemn Hollywood for its gilded, ostentatiousness and concessions.
French filmmaker Bertrand Tavernier, not without humor, considered it "a lively challenge of underplaying", judging that in his performances he pushed too much on the saw.
For the beautiful Paul Newman, to whom the roles came as a tray, the profession was not always so tender.
However, the first lovers played less often than the outsiders: neurotics, alcoholics, rags and despair, whose decline and rebellion reflected in his perfect features.
As a director, Newman revealed little-known pages of his shy sensibilities.
His 1968 film Rachel, Rachel (based on the novel by Canadian Margaret Laurence), starring his wife Joanne Woodward, features a sensitive female portrait full of melancholy.
His son Scott, whom he lost due to an overdose, was given the 1984 film Harry and Son, a work full of shame and sadness.
In a tribute to Newman yesterday, his great friend and former co-star Robert Redford (played together in The Sting and Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid) lamented, "His presence has made my life and this country better."
Generosity, love of life, these are the main characteristics of the deceased actor.
Aside from his legendary career, there is also a great fighter for civil rights, ecology, an independent film, an opponent of the decline of Hollywood.
We used to see his likeness on bottles of wine vinegar, sauces, cookies and other foods, which we thought might be rather distasteful, although at first it was a gag.
However, profits from the sale went to the account of his Foundation for Heavy Childhood.
Thus, rather than let himself be swayed by glory, Newman was engaged in society until the last moment.
He left a letter to his five daughters that read: “Always and to the end, your father was grateful to his happy planet.
It was an honor to have been here.”
And it was an honor for us to be able to follow the life path of such a bright-eyed and generous American artist.
And besides, after all, a model citizen.
