The psychology of trumping: why do we spend more money?
At auctions, customers are willing to spend more money, overvalue the goods.
The neurological and economic foundations of this well-known – and seemingly irrational – behavior have been uncovered by researchers in the field of neurology and economics at New York University.
According to their study, published in the journal Science, people don’t want to be left behind in an eBay auction, so they’d rather pay too high a price.
Research with the help of an experimental auction tried to map the scheme of this "game" in the nervous system.
One group of volunteers bet, the other group took part in the auction, using the method of functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) to study the active areas of the brain of experimental subjects.
In both games, the participants could win money, but in the auction game, an important element of which is to trump the other side, the whole under the cerebral cortex, called the striatum, began to work intensively when losing.
This area of the brain, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the "self-rewarding" mechanism of the nervous system.
According to the researchers, the price screwing can therefore be explained by the effort to avoid a sharp reaction of the striata.
To support their theory, members of the research team among economists conducted a financial cross-sectional survey.
Under different conditions, three groups were bidding against one partner.
The control group was simply told what the fair value of the product was, and they made the bets.
In addition, members of the other group were promised that if they exit the game, they would receive an additional $15 for the reward.
The third group, on the other hand, received $15 before the auction, but in the event of a loss, its members also lost this money.
The difference between the two groups, therefore, consisted in the fact that one was emphasized as a win and the other as a loss.
The members of the group playing "against loss" were, however, willing to go higher than it was in the control and "winning" group, which confirms the hypothesis of neurologists.
"These results cannot be deduced from any previously existing economic theory.
In fact, they have so far explained the phenomena observed in auctioning joys of victory and avoiding risk.
Until neurological imaging methods helped us to resolve the contradiction between these two theories so that we now have a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: when to see a doctor?
About half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and in Hungary, this chronic liver disease is listed among the leading causes of death.
The number of domestic cases of hepatitis infection is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand of them are treated. The reason for this is that patients often do not know that they are infected.
The name hepatitis is a generic name for infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
In their symptoms there are many similarities, the inflammation of the liver and jaundice is symptomatic, but the causes of the disease and the diseases caused by them differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses spread in two main ways depending on the origin of the disease: hepatitis type A and E by the digestive system (for example, by infected food, water), hepatitis type B, C, D and other blood and body fluid viruses (sperm, vaginal secretions).
Travelers should in any case protect themselves by vaccination against virus A and B, there is no vaccine against virus type C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after ingestion of an infected food, usually accompanied by nausea, weakness, abdominal problems, urge to vomit.
Then on the skin and the whites of the eyes, a jaundice, a lighted stool and dark urine are formed. The treatment can take up to two to three weeks.
Every year, one million people worldwide die from a more serious type of the disease, liver cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason is that it is estimated that only one in ten infected people is treated with medication.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if not treated, it can lead to liver cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most of the infected do not even know about their disease, the origin of the disease destroys the liver cells inadvertently, and so the first symptoms appear in many cases in 20-30 years.
Therefore, it is very important to prevent early, conduct regular screening.
In three groups, this disease occurs much more often than on average: among people who had had a blood transfusion before 1991, among drug users, and among people with tattoos.
Currently, the estimated worldwide number of individuals infected with chronic hepatitis C virus is 200 million.
Since the disease can be demonstrated by a routine laboratory examination, a person should contact his/her doctor if he/she experiences any symptom of unknown origin.
With early detection, the disease is curable, the virus can be removed from the body, thus preventing the spread of the infection and preventing the formation of cancer.
September 30 is the World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized by organizations representing the sick worldwide in 2004.
Its aim is to draw attention to the chronic inflammation of the liver caused by these viruses, the causes of its formation and the importance of early recognition of the disease.
