Scientists from the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment, exploring how faith in the god of pain affects a person, the British newspaper Telegraph reported.
As part of a rather bizarre survey, 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists were subjected to electric shocks, while all observed a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude a large part of the pain.
Thanks to the technique, a detailed examination of the human brain showed that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain that is responsible for the regulation of pain.
The research is the first in a series of studies involving academics, scientists, philosophers and theologians from different parts of the university.
The exact test was carried out by attaching a flashing instrument to the left hand of the test subject, which emitted electric shocks.
The researchers asked the participants to observe two paintings: the 17th-century Sassoferrat’s Virgin Mary and the 15th-century Leonardo da Vinci’s Lady with a crossbow, painted in the 15th century.
The authors of the research hoped that looking at the Virgin Mary would bring about a certain state of piety in the faithful, while da Vinci’s painting was chosen because it was not very different from the first and seemed to them a calming impression.
The experimental subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner and during this time received 20 electroshocks in four successive parts, while separately watching the image with a religious or general theme.
Catholics said that when they looked at the Virgin Mary, they felt "safe," as if they were "taken care of" and "calm down, they were filled with peace."
When watching a religiously-themed painting, they felt 12 percent less pain than when they had Leonardo’s work in front of them.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the research, believes that a similar effect can be achieved with the help of any highly impressive image even among atheists, just need to find the right photo.
"We would have to find a picture that they would perceive very positively, from the position of a mother or father," the psychologist said.
