Intelligent car mimics the flight of a bumblebee
What would be the best method of developing technologies capable of preventing collisions, if not imitating the detectors of obstacles occurring in the world of nature?
For example, bees.
The initial strategic idea of the surprising project, presented at the Japanese CEATEC fair, was to introduce engineers from the company Nissan <0xC5><0x8C>mel<0xC3><0xA1>ci. It was about how to build a new generation of systems to prevent crashes.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has designed a biomimetic robotic control system of the BR23C type, a robotic mini-car equipped with bee features, with the ultimate goal of helping to create a system that can eliminate all collisions.
“During the flight, each bee creates its own personal oval-shaped space, which is actually very similar to our security protective packaging,” said Kazuhiro Doi, the brand’s director general for technology PR and R&D.
An important role is played by the compound eyes, which allow the bees to see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees.
Engineers used the idea of a laser rangefinder to copy the function of the compound eye.
It identifies obstacles up to 2 metres ahead of the BR23C in the 180-degree field of view, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately transforms into an operation aimed at preventing a collision.
The obstacle is caught within a fraction of a second, then the robotic car begins to imitate the movements of the bees and by turning the wheels in the range necessary to prevent a collision immediately changes direction.
Unlike any existing system, this maneuver is carried out in a completely instinctive way.
"If this were not the case, the robotic car would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshijuki Ando, head of the Mobility Laboratory and Robotic Car Project.
They need to respond instinctively and immediately, as this technology fits the most vulnerable and innermost layer of security packaging, within which a crash is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what the bee is doing to avoid the other bees.
This process should not take longer than the blink of an eye.
However, unlike bees, this movement cannot be directed upwards, downwards or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and only in the direction in which the wheels can be rotated.
Instead of the endless possibilities offered to bees when avoiding, only the possibility of rotating, accelerating and slowing down was applied in the case of a robotic car.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy density, meaning they have a longer life than lithium-ion variants.
According to Andoa, instinctive, intelligent responses are important, not the ability to process, let alone store data.
This mechanism must process and respond to only a few incoming signals per second.
There is no need to store and respond to them using intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so it constantly uses only memory of a few kilobytes in size.
It does not require memory with a gigabyte or megabyte capacity.
This is the first step in the development of an immediate-avoidance technology that Nissan estimates could reach mass-produced cars within a decade.
Another option of application may be to connect the unit to the GPS satellite navigation system, which, after avoiding obstacles in the way, would lead the motorist to the specified final destination.
