The $700 billion bailout bill, which is to be split into several installments and is aimed at buying out poor-quality bank loans, is already in writing.
Half of the amount will be used in the first round.
After further negotiations, which ended only on Saturday after midnight of U.S. Eastern Time, congressional representatives reached an agreement in a few days to debate a $700 billion bailout package, Reuters reported.
"We have made significant progress," said Nancy Pelosi, the Democratic Speaker of the House of Representatives, who said only the signing of the agreement remained.
The compromise on the package was also backed by both presidential candidates Barack Obama and John McCain.
Finance Minister Henry Paulson said of the compromise outcome: “The programme will work and be effective, but further steps need to be taken.”
The written version of the package was published before the opening of Asian markets on Sunday at 8 p.m. Washington time (that is, on Monday at 2 a.m. Central European time), but it did not cause any special rise on the exchanges.
On Monday, the House of Representatives will vote on the draft legal standard, named after the Emergency Economic Stabilization Act of 2008, which is to be established by the program, and then it will be a matter for the Senate.
President George W. Bush spoke to Pelosi on Saturday evening, after reports of the deal were also welcomed at the White House.
"We are pleased with the progress made last night and appreciate the efforts of both sides to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy," White House spokesman Tony Fratto said in a statement.
After all, the program is different from the Bush administration’s original proposal that a total of $700 billion should be spent on the purchase of low-quality securities secured by mortgages at once.
Now it is possible to spend a maximum of $700 billion in the first half, in such a way that $250 billion will be used immediately after the matter is expected to be decided by Congress on Monday, and the Ministry of Finance will buy for them securities secured by mortgages, which are valued as low-quality, the fate of the president will be decided by 100 percent.
The program will be controlled by a special corps, of which the chairman of the Federal Reserve Bank will also be a member.
Spending the second half of $700 billion will depend on the next decision of Congress.
In the sense of the law, the Ministry of Finance can apply a combined tactic: it can simultaneously buy off low-quality loans, mortgages and securities secured by mortgages, or other "poisonous" loans.
Purchases can be made within the framework of auctions and directly, the competent representatives of the Ministry said.
The legal standard will allow the companies concerned to participate in an insurance programme in which the Ministry of Finance will provide them with a guarantee on the funds representing a cause for concern, for which the companies will pay a price corresponding to the amount of the expected damages.
As Henry Paulson said, the law provides the necessary means to spend up to $700 billion to meet the urgent requirements of the U.S. financial system, whether it is a large purchase of bad assets, their insurance, or preventing the systemic risk associated with the collapse of some of the assets.
"We will take the necessary steps to be prepared to introduce the law as soon as it is signed," he added.
On the contrary, the heads of banks who are in trouble and waiting for the help of the state can count on the government to reduce their apostasy - which is simply called a "golden parachute" in the offshore slang.
Their payment will only be limited in certain cases, in addition, these restrictions will depend on the method of assistance provided by the Ministry.
The restriction basically means that if the Ministry buys in the auction, a tax surcharge will be imposed on the golden parachutes, if the fallen bank directors are not sent straight to retirement.
In the case of a direct purchase of low-quality loans, the government will take aggressive steps in order to ensure that the money for the management is not exaggerated.
It should be added that existing contracts on gold parachutes will not be changed, the restriction only applies to new contracts, which is intended to be another incentive to participate in the programme.
“This is the first time in American history that a statutory cap on the remuneration of CEOs will be in force,” said House Financial Services Committee Chairman Barney Frank.
In addition, the state will have the right to obtain a share in the participating banks, thereby reducing the risk of taxpayers, since once the economy and the saved bank are on their feet, they can also make a profit on this transaction.
The proposal plan states that over the next five years, the president must submit a proposal to Congress to determine how the expected losses from the financial sector can be repaid to taxpayers.
On both sides, of course, there were voices in connection with the plan of doubt.
"This is not what the U.S. citizens have asked us to do, this is not going to protect taxpayer dollars," Darrell Issa, a Republican from California, said.
His Democratic colleague from Ohio, Mary Kaptur, judges that the adoption of the provision was urged by precisely those responsible for the collapse of Wall Street.
Industrial prices continued to rise
Domestic sales prices in the industry increased by 0.1 per cent in August 2008 compared to the previous month, compared to 12.9 per cent in August 2007, the Central Statistical Office announced.
Export sales prices in the industry were up 1.1 percent year-on-year compared to July 2008, down 3.9 percent year-on-year.
As a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent compared to the previous month, increasing by 3.2 per cent year-on-year.
Domestic sales prices in the industry increased by only a minimum of 0.1 percent compared to the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in the manufacturing sectors also rose slightly, by 0.1 per cent, compared to July.
The largest increase in prices occurred in August 2008 in the leather and footwear industry (2.8 per cent), mainly due to an inter-monthly increase in prices in the manufacture of handbags and saddlery products by 4.6 per cent, respectively, and shoe production by 2.5 per cent.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical raw materials caused a significant monthly price increase in the chemical materials and products production sector (1.6%).
The decrease in prices occurred in the oil processing sector (1.4 percent), the production of electric machines and appliances (0.9 percent), as well as - to a minimum - in the woodworking sector (0.1 percent).
Prices in the field of paper production and publishing and printing activities have not changed.
In other sectors of the manufacturing industry, we measured price increases in the range of 0.2 - 0.9 percent.
In the electricity, gas and water production and distribution sector, which is of great importance to the domestic sales of the industry, prices rose by 0.3 percent in August, mainly due to the continuing impact of the officially determined increase in gas prices from 1 July.
In the twelve-month comparison of domestic sales in individual sectors of the processing industry, prices rose the most in the professional oil processing sector (32.4 percent).
In the metalworking industry it was possible to observe 13,2 percent, in the production of food products, beverages and tobacco products, which has a decisive weight, then 11 percent price increase.
The decrease in prices occurred in the textile and textile products (2.5 per cent) and electrical machinery and appliances (0.3 per cent).
In other manufacturing sectors, the rate of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 per cent.
Overall, prices in the manufacturing sector rose by 10.2 per cent over the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas and water production and distribution sector exceeded the prices of the previous year by 18.7 per cent.
In terms of segmentation by sector focus, domestic sales in August showed the highest monthly price increase (0,7 per cent) in the material asset production sectors.
In the sectors producing consumer goods, prices rose by 0.3 per cent, in the energy processing and further processing sectors, prices did not change compared to the previous month.
The largest increase in prices compared to the same month of the previous year was observed in the energy processing and further processing sectors (16.8%) in August 2008.
In the sectors producing consumer goods, we measured a price increase of 6.8 percent, while in the case of tangible assets, we measured a price decrease of 1.4 percent.
Export sales prices of industrial products measured in forints increased by 1.1 percent in August compared to the previous month, down by 3.9 percent in a 12-month comparison.
Our domestic payment decreased by 1.7 per cent against the euro in one month, by 7.1 per cent against the dollar, compared with 7.5 per cent against the euro in August 2007 and by 15.9 per cent against the dollar.
